13 min read
Just now

--

I’ve written in the past about a Pokémon fan game I’ve built, including describing the way I laid out the battle system to run autonomously with a series of callbacks and references to make everything run smoothly.
Recently, I dove back into this complex system to add Abilities which are additional capabilities a Pokémon can have. What makes them complicated is that they can be triggered in many different ways, and their effects are very diverse. This presented a number of challenges in adding them to the battle system. Additionally, backporting existing Pokémon to have these abilities caused more issues.
This blog post tells of the story of this feature.
Interfaces
Press enter or click to view image in full size

First I updated the data interfaces to lay the foundation. In our database, Pokémon are defined in regional files (ie. kanto.ts, johto.ts, etc.) with a single types.ts to define the core interface.
export interface PokemonDocBuilder {
// ...
/** 0th: var0 ability. 1st/2nd: ordinary abilities. 3rd: hidden ability. */
abilities?: [AbilityId | null, AbilityId, AbilityId, AbilityId]
mega?: Mega
megax?: Mega
megay?: Mega
megaz?: Mega
}interface Mega {
attack: number
defense: number
spAttack: number
spDefense: number
speed: number
type1?: Type
type2?: Type | false
// FIXME: Make this mandatory
ability?: AbilityId
move: MoveId[]
weight: number
pokedex: string
}
You can see how I’m defining the abilities as an array of exactly four items. Every Pokémon should have four abilities defined, even if I need to define the same ability twice. For instance, Chikorita has Overgrow as both the first and second abilities. Having this static list will help the TypeScript compiler catch any Pokémon which are missing data.
Now I can add abilities by using their string definition, which will make lookup possible.
// shared/src/pokemon/johto.ts
export const johtoBuilder = {
"potw-152": ensurePkmnBuilder({
"species": "Chikorita",
// ... stats ...
abilities: [null, 'Overgrow', 'OvergrowI2', 'LeafGuard'],
// ...
}),
}Each Pokémon caught encodes a 2-bit index which then points to, based on the database lookup, which ability it should actually have.
// shared/src/badge3.ts
const rawAbilityIndex = formPkmn.abilities?.indexOf(personality.ability!) ?? -1
const abilityIndex = rawAbilityIndex !== -1 ? rawAbilityIndex : 1;
// This index is then packed into a single byte alongside other traits
return (variantId << 4) | (genderId << 2) | (shiny ? 2 : 0) | (affection ? 1 : 0); // Simplified for illustrationWhen creating a new Pokémon for a player, the ability can be obtained randomly.
static create(badgeId: string) {
const badge = this.fromLegacy(badgeId)
//
badge.personality.ability = (() => {
if (Math.random() < 0.45) {
return dbPkmn.abilities?.[1] ?? 'PlaceholderPower'
}
if (Math.random() < 0.9) {
return dbPkmn.abilities?.[2] ?? 'PlaceholderPower'
}
return dbPkmn.abilities?.[3] ?? 'PlaceholderPower'
})()
return badge
}Encoding every ability into just two bits, not even a single byte, saves a lot of space in Firestore and that helps players store even more Pokémon. As we’ll see later, this did set a trap for us when it came to evolutions and regional forms.
Battle Hooks
We define a central Ability interface in our battle system which defines a number of optional hooks that our ability logic can implement to have particular effects, allowing them to react at the appropriate times.
// shared/src/battle/types.ts
export interface Ability {
name: string
flavor: string
turn: number
onBattleStart?: (caster: Pokemon, target: Pokemon) => Log
onEnterBattle?: (caster: Pokemon, field: Field, prefix: Prefix, party: Pokemon[], targets: Pokemon[]) => Log
onCasterMove?: (input: MoveInput) => Log
onAfterMove?: (input: MoveInput) => Log
onBeforeMoveHit?:(caster: Pokemon, target: Pokemon, input: MoveInput) => Log
onTargetMove?: (input: MoveInput) => Log
onMoveHit?: (caster: Pokemon, target: Pokemon, input: MoveInput) => Log
onCriticalHit?: (target: Pokemon) => Log
onTurnEnd?: (caster: Pokemon, party: Pokemon[], targets: Pokemon[], field: Field) => Log
onItemUsed?: (caster: Pokemon, input: MoveInput) => Log
onNewWeather?: (caster: Pokemon, oldWeather: WeatherEvent, newWeather: WeatherEvent, party: Pokemon[]) => Log
onNewTerrain?: (caster: Pokemon, oldTerrain: TerrainEvent, newTerrain: TerrainEvent) => Log
onFainted?: (caster: Pokemon, field: Field, prefix: Prefix) => Log
}I have a massive map which lists every ability:
export const AbilityDex: Record<string, Ability> = {
Overgrow: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Overgrow', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Boosts Grass-type moves in a pinch',
onCasterMove: (input) => boostTypeInPinch(input.caster, input.move, 'Grass'),
}),
}cloneAbilityWithNewIndex('Overgrow', 2)
The cloneAbility function creates and adds to the map a new ability called OvergrowI2. This is done because Chikorita has Overgrow in two slots and I want to ensure that the ability does the same thing while being placed in the second slot. For some evolutions, this does make a difference. Otherwise it would never have that second slot filled.
Implementing the Basics
At the start, I only had a few hooks: onBattleStart, onCasterMove, onTargetMove, onMoveHit, onTurnEnd, and onItemUsed.
Adaptability: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Adaptability', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Strengthens same type moves',
onCasterMove: ({caster, move}) => {
if (caster.type1 === move.type || caster.type2 === move.type) {
move.power *= 1.333;
}
return new Log()
},
})This was enough to implement roughly half of the 300 in-game abilities. I was able to take advantage of existing helpers to make the implementation faster.
SpeedBoost: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Speed Boost', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Raises speed at the end of the turn',
onTurnEnd: (caster) => {
return BUFF_STAT(caster, {caster, targetPrefix: 'Your'}, 'speed')
},
}),However, there were several abilities that were still not possible yet such as Levitate and Armor Tail. The onMoveHit only ran after the move hit the opponent, meaning we needed an additional hook to intercept a move before being hit. So I added onBeforeMoveHit:
Levitate: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Levitate', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Grants immunity to Ground-type moves',
onBeforeMoveHit: (caster, target, {move}) => {
const log = new Log()
if (move.type === 'Ground' && move.name !== 'Thousand Arrows') {
log.add(`It had no effect on the floating ${target.species}`)
move.failed = true
}
return log
}
})Entry Hazards
Next, I needed to add a new hook that ran when the Pokémon entered the field, not just when the battle started. For example, the ability Intimidate only runs when the Pokémon is sent out. If the Pokémon switches out and in again, the ability needs to activate again.
Intimidate: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Intimidate', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Cuts attack on entry',
onEnterBattle: (caster, _, __, ___, targets) => {
const l = new Log()
l.add(`${caster.species}'s Intimidate activated`)
targets.forEach(t => {
l.push(BUFF_STAT(t, {caster, targetPrefix: 'Opposing'}, 'attack', -1))
})
return l
},
})I needed to add far more logic to the BUFF_STAT function to handle a number of abilities and their conditions. These abilities can affect the stat multiplier, block stat drops, or change the target.

export const BUFF_STAT = (caster: Pokemon, input: BuffStatParams, stat: Stat, stages = 1): Log => {
if (caster.heldItemKey === 'covertcloak' && stages < 0) return new Log() const log = new Log()
if (input.field?.sides[input.targetPrefix]?.mist && stages < 0) {
log.add('The mist prevents stats from being lowered.')
return log // Exit early
}
if (stages < 0 && caster !== input.caster && input.caster.heldItemKey === 'clearamulet') {
log.add('The Clear Amulet prevents stats from being dropped')
return log // Exit early
}
if (caster.statBuffs[stat] >= 6 && stages > 0) {
log.add(`${caster.species}'s ${stat} won't go any higher!`)
return log
}
if (caster.statBuffs[stat] <= -6 && stages < 0) {
log.add(`${caster.species}'s ${stat} won't go any lower!`)
return log
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Simple') {
stages *= 2
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Contrary') {
stages *= -1
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Illuminate' && stat === 'accuracy' && stages < 0) {
stages = 0
}
if (['Hyper Cutter', 'Oblivious'].includes(caster.ability?.name ?? '') && stat === 'attack' && stages < 0) {
stages = 0
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Guard Dog' && stat === 'attack' && stages < 0) {
stages = 1
}
if (['Clear Body', 'White Smoke', 'Full Metal Body'].includes(caster.ability?.name ?? '') && stages < 0) {
stages = 0
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Mirror Armor' && stages < 0 && input.target) {
caster = input.target
}
caster.statBuffs[stat] += stages
// Clamp -6 <= stat <= 6
caster.statBuffs[stat] = Math.max(-6, Math.min(6, caster.statBuffs[stat]))
log.add(`${caster.species}'s ${stat} ${statMgs[stages]}`)
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Competitive') {
log.add(`${caster.species}'s Competitive activated`)
caster.statBuffs.spAttack = Math.max(-6, Math.min(6, caster.statBuffs.spAttack + 2))
log.add(`${caster.species}'s spAttack ${statMgs[2]}`)
}
if (caster.ability?.name === 'Defiant') {
log.add(`${caster.species}'s Defiant activated`)
caster.statBuffs.attack = Math.max(-6, Math.min(6, caster.statBuffs.attack + 2))
log.add(`${caster.species}'s attack ${statMgs[2]}`)
}
return log
}
Higher Complexity
As I reached the final dozens, I started running into signature abilities and environmental abilities which required even more complex and specialized handling.
For instance, the onCriticalHit hook was added only for the ability Anger Point.
AngerPoint: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Anger Point', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Maxes out attack on critical hits',
onCriticalHit: (target) => {
const log = new Log()
log.add(`${target.species}'s Anger Point activated`)
log.add(`${target.species}'s attack reached its zenith`)
target.statBuffs.attack = 6
return log
}
}),The hook onFainted was added for abilities that trigger when the Pokémon faints like Aftermath.
Aftermath: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Aftermath', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Damages the attacker when this Pokémon faints',
onMoveHit: (_, __, input) => {
if (input.target.currentHp === 0 && input.caster.ability?.name !== 'Damp') {
// This is a KO
const l = new Log()
l.add(`${input.target.species}'s Aftermath activated`)
l.push(logDamage(input.caster, input.caster.totalHp/4, true))
return l
}
return new Log()
},
}),Abilities like Swift Swim change Pokémon behavior in different weather, requiring new hooks like onNewWeather and onNewTerrain.
SwiftSwim: assert<Ability>({
name: 'Swift Swim', turn: 0,
flavor: 'Boosts speed in rain',
onNewWeather: (caster, prev, next) => {
if (prev.name === 'Rain') {
caster.speed /= 2
}
if (next.name === 'Rain') {
caster.speed *= 2
}
return new Log()
}
}),Additionally, I had to expand the interfaces representing the fields to track persistent ability-related effects.
export interface Field {
// ...
primordialsea: number
desolateland: number
cloudnine: number
darkaura: number
fairyaura: number
aurabreak: number
neutralizinggas: number
vesselofruin: number
swordofruin: number
tabletsofruin: number
beadsofruin: number
}export interface SideField {
// ...
steelySpirit: number
battery: number
powerSpot: number
arenaTrap: number
magnetPull: number
unnerve: number
victoryStar: number
plusminus: number
}
A Dugtrio enters the field and its Arena Trap ability activates to prevent the opposing side from switching out. When it faints, those Pokémon are allowed to switch out again. However, when there are two Dugtrio and one faints, the ability is still being applied. So I need to keep track of the number of Arena Traps and only allow switching when this value is zero. For other abilities, like Steely Spirit, this acts as a multiplier to all Steel-type moves. At the start of the battle, the steelySpirit value is 1 as default.
